The epistle concludes with some excellent moral maxims and reflections. Horace, aster giving Lollius precepts respecting the mode of life which he is to pursue with the Great, lays down also some rules for his conduct towards himself. He endeavours chiefly to make him sensible‚ that happiness does not consist in the favour of princes, but must be the fruit of our own reflection and care, and a steady pur- pose of keeping our passions within the bounds of moderation.—97. Secretum iter, et fallentis semita vitae. “A retired route, and the path of an humble life ;'' i. e. of a life that pasees unno- ticed by the world. Fallentis is here equivalent to oculos hominum latentis. It is not the poet's design to create in Lollius a disgust of his present way of life, or make him quit the court to enjoy retirement.
